er argues that for seculars today the possibility of a devoted life, the practice of felicity in history, still remains. Spirit now names a necessary "prosthesis," a locus for regenerating the elemental commons of our interdependent flesh and thus for cultivating spacious and fearless empathy, forbearance, and generosity.Her theological poetics, though based in Christianity, are frequently in conversation with other religions resident in our postcolonial cities.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 23. Jul 2020) 0aCities and townsxReligious aspects. 0aGlobalizationxReligious aspects. 4aDisability. 4abeauty. 4acity. 4afear. 4aflesh. 4aforbearance. 4apain. 4aspirit. 4atheology. 4aurban. 7aRELIGION / Christian Theology / Pneumatology.2bisacsh08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertFUP eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013z978311070729840uhttps://doi.org/10.1515/9780823253937zCo-access DOI >> click Walter de Gruyter40uhttps://www.degruyter.com/isbn/9780823253937423Coveruhttps://www.degruyter.com/cover/covers/9780823253937.jpg  a978-3-11-070729-8  FUP eBook-Package Backlist 2000-2013c2000d2013  aEBA_BACKALL  aEBA_CL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EBACKALL  aEBA_EBKALL  aEBA_ECL_PLTLJSIS  aEBA_EEBKALL  aEBA_ESSHALL  aEBA_PPALL  aEBA_SSHALL  aGBV-deGruyter-alles  aPDA11SSHE  aPDA13ENGE  aPDA17SSHEE  aPDA5EBK